      The Facebook Files
   =20
 =20
Here is the=C2=A0New York Times=C2=A0on=C2=A0Facebook Inc. whistle-blower F=
rances Haugen, who disclosed a bunch of internal documents about all the ba=
d stuff that Facebook allegedly does:In an interview with =E2=80=9C60 Minut=
es=E2=80=9D that aired Sunday, Ms. Haugen, 37, said she had grown alarmed b=
y what she saw at Facebook. The company repeatedly put its own interests fi=
rst rather than the public=E2=80=99s interest, she said. So she copied page=
s of Facebook=E2=80=99s internal research and decided to do something about=
 it.=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve seen a bunch of social networks and it was substa=
ntially worse at Facebook than what I had seen before,=E2=80=9D Ms. Haugen =
said. She added, =E2=80=9CFacebook, over and over again, has shown it choos=
es profit over safety.=E2=80=9DOkay fine. Facebook is a for-profit company =
with obligations to its shareholders, and at various points it has a choice=
 between doing pro-social things that are expensive or doing anti-social th=
ings that maximize its profits. Sometimes (she asserts, and I don=E2=80=99t=
 particularly disagree)=C2=A0it chooses profit over public good. This is no=
t a huge surprise, incentives being what they are, but it is good for polic=
ymakers and the public to know about the particular cases. It is good=C2=A0=
because, if we know about these choices, we can make informed decisions abo=
ut regulation and enforcement. If Facebook sometimes chose to=C2=A0break th=
e law=C2=A0to maximize profit, then regulators should punish it. If everyth=
ing that Facebook does to maximize profits is=C2=A0legal, but some of it is=
=C2=A0horrible, then we should write=C2=A0new laws=C2=A0to make the horribl=
e stuff illegal. If Facebook does things that are bad for the world then po=
licymakers should try to make it stop.=C2=A0Basic stuff.But here is another=
 fact from that same Times article:Ms. Haugen has also filed a whistle-blow=
er complaint with the Securities and Exchange Commission, accusing Facebook=
 of misleading investors with public statements that did not match its inte=
rnal actions. ...Ms. Haugen=E2=80=99s complaint to the S.E.C. was based on =
her document trove and consisted of many cover letters, seven of which were=
 obtained by The Times. Each letter detailed a different topic =E2=80=94 su=
ch as Facebook=E2=80=99s role in spreading misinformation after the 2020 el=
ection and the impact its products have on teenagers=E2=80=99 mental health=
 =E2=80=94 and accused the company of making =E2=80=9Cmaterial misrepresent=
ations and omissions in statements to investors and prospective investors.=
=E2=80=9DShe was so concerned about Facebook putting profits over the publi=
c good that she filed a complaint with the SEC about how Facebook misleads=
=C2=A0investors. Schematically, the general form of this complaint is:=09Fa=
cebook maximizes profits for shareholders instead of caring about the publi=
c good.=09In its public statements, however, it says =E2=80=9Cwe care about=
 the public good, not just maximizing profits for shareholders.=E2=80=9D=09=
Shareholders are deceived: They think that Facebook is committed to the pub=
lic good and are sad to find out that it is only maximizing profits for the=
m.=09Therefore Facebook should give the shareholders some money, to compens=
ate them for this=C2=A0deception. (Or it should give money to the SEC, whic=
h might share some of it with the shareholders and some of it with the whis=
tle-blower, to vindicate=C2=A0the right=C2=A0of shareholders not to be dece=
ived.)This is=C2=A0weird, right? That the shareholders are harmed by the co=
mpany maximizing profits more than they expected? I don=E2=80=99t mean that=
 it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0wrong, or=C2=A0logically inconsistent; it makes sense if=
 you supply a few assumptions. (Something like: =E2=80=9CFacebook went too =
far in maximizing short-term profits, in a way that is bad for its brand im=
age and public perception, which will cause it to lose customers and be mor=
e strictly regulated, which will be bad for profits, and for shareholders, =
in the long run.=E2=80=9D)I just want to suggest that it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0wei=
rd. There is a classic view that the interests of=C2=A0shareholders=C2=A0an=
d the interests of=C2=A0society sometimes diverge, that sometimes companies=
 put the financial interests of their shareholders (profit) above the good =
of society, and that an important job of government is to find and regulate=
 those cases of market failure. It=E2=80=99s cheaper to dump your industria=
l waste in a river than to pay for safe disposal, so companies do that to m=
aximize profits, so governments write laws to prevent them from doing that,=
 etc. The shareholders say =E2=80=9Cfocus on profit above all else=E2=80=9D=
 and society says =E2=80=9Cwell not above all=C2=A0else.=E2=80=9D And then =
companies have an optimization problem: They have to maximize profit, const=
rained only by staying within the rules.This is such a standard view that=
=C2=A0a couple of years ago the chief executive officers of a bunch of big =
companies said, in effect, =E2=80=9Cwe are going to stop caring only about =
shareholders and start caring about society.=E2=80=9D This was viewed as a=
=C2=A0big change. You have shareholders, you have society, they are adverse=
 to each other, you have to pick. The CEOs were like =E2=80=9Cusually we ha=
ve picked shareholders but now sometimes we will pick society.=E2=80=9D[1]B=
ut I think this model is wrong. I mean, perhaps it was once right, but now =
it isn=E2=80=99t. Now shareholders increasingly come to the companies they =
own and say =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t maximize profits for us, do what is best=
 for society.=E2=80=9DThe basic theory is about long-term sustainability an=
d internalization of externalities. The theory is that if a company chooses=
 profit over some other legitimate stakeholder interest (being nice to cust=
omers, treating workers fairly, not polluting, not undermining democracy, e=
tc.), then its profits will not be sustainable. Eventually the customers wi=
ll take their business elsewhere, the workers won=E2=80=99t produce good wo=
rk, or governments will pass laws about=C2=A0pollution and democracy-underm=
ining that will destroy the company=E2=80=99s business. In the long run, ex=
ternalities are internalized: If you make a profit by harming society, even=
tually society is going to send you a bill for that harm, with interest. Lo=
ng-term shareholders want you to profit=C2=A0without=C2=A0harming society, =
so that you can keep profiting in the future.This theory has gotten a ton o=
f traction and attention in the last decade. In particular it is=C2=A0at th=
e core of ESG investing, investing that takes into account environmental, s=
ocial and governance factors. We  talked last month about a presentation fr=
om ESG-ish activist fund Engine No. 1 LLC, which focused explicitly on this=
 internalization-of-externalities argument.[2] And I say =E2=80=9Cthe last =
decade=E2=80=9D because of this article by Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Kate Mackenz=
ie from last Friday about =E2=80=9CHow the Finance World Started Turning Ag=
ainst Fossil Fuels=E2=80=9D:A quiet celebration took place in London last m=
onth. It marked the 10th anniversary of the =E2=80=9CCarbon Bubble=E2=80=9D=
 report, published by the think tank Carbon Tracker Initiative, that=E2=80=
=99s become one of the most influential arguments against burning fossil fu=
els. =E2=80=A6Carbon Tracker concluded that only a fifth of the 2.3 trillio=
n tons of hydrocarbons could be extracted and used. The rest would have to =
be left in the ground. It was a completely counterintuitive proposal to the=
 corporate world. All that coal, oil and gas contributed to the value of co=
mpanies and assets that sat in portfolios from New York to Hong Kong. Even =
if the goal was only partly realized, those holdings would plummet.=E2=80=
=9CInvestors are thus left exposed to the risk of unburnable carbon,=E2=80=
=9D the report said. They would be =E2=80=9Cstranded assets=E2=80=9D ...The=
 Carbon Bubble report introduced a completely new way of looking at the pro=
blem. Its authors pointed out another truth: the fossil fuel business had t=
o go away if the planet were to survive, and being the last one out the doo=
r would be a colossal financial mistake.That is an argument of the form =E2=
=80=9Csure you can make a lot of money for shareholders now by pumping out =
oil, but in the long run you won=E2=80=99t be allowed to, so as shareholder=
s we want you to stop doing so much of that.=E2=80=9D That argument was in =
some sense=C2=A0invented=C2=A010 years ago, and now it is close to a consen=
sus among big institutional investors. Engine No. 1 got=C2=A0Exxon Mobil Co=
rp. shareholders to  throw out some of the company=E2=80=99s directors for,=
 roughly speaking, not taking climate change seriously enough. Just as a ma=
tter of shareholder value.But while this theory is closely associated with =
ESG investing, they are=C2=A0not identical. We have  also talked about it t=
hrough the lens of index investing and common ownership: If the big diversi=
fied shareholders own=C2=A0all=C2=A0the companies, they care relatively les=
s about any one company=E2=80=99s profit maximization and more about increa=
sing the overall value available to all companies, which is not quite the s=
ame thing as increasing the overall welfare of the world but which is=C2=A0=
related=C2=A0to that. Broadly diversified institutional investors, the argu=
ment goes, will care more about the externalities created by any one compan=
y because they own all the other companies. If a company pollutes, that wil=
l be bad for other companies, and so the shareholders will tell it to stop.=
 If a company develops a Covid-19 vaccine, that will be good for other comp=
anies, and so the shareholders will push it to do that. Common ownership of=
 all the companies is a new way to coordinate economic activity, and it mak=
es sense that it would  solve certain coordination problems=C2=A0and cause =
companies to take a broader view.[3] We  talked last week about a sharehold=
er proposal at Fox Corp. demanding that it give its viewers =E2=80=9Can acc=
urate understanding of current events through the exercise of journalistic =
integrity,=E2=80=9D because that would be=C2=A0good for the world and, thus=
, for the other companies in its shareholders' portfolios.Or of course I ta=
lk all the time here about how =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=
=80=9D: Every bad thing that a public company does can be described as a fr=
aud on its shareholders, and then they (or the SEC) can sue. In particular,=
 when a company pollutes or mistreats customers or harasses workers or what=
ever =E2=80=94=C2=A0when the  primary victim of the company=E2=80=99s actio=
n is not the shareholders but some other identifiable group =E2=80=94 share=
holders will sue it for securities fraud. In the old, classic theory, the c=
ompany was doing bad things to other stakeholders (employees, customers, th=
e environment)=C2=A0to make money for shareholders; the other stakeholders =
might sue the company for the bad things, but the amoral profit-maximizing =
shareholders would say =E2=80=9Cgood for you, exploit more workers to make =
money for us.=E2=80=9D In the new theory, the shareholders say =E2=80=9Cit =
is bad for the long-term value of our shares when you do bad things to othe=
r people, so=C2=A0we=C2=A0will sue you for doing bad things to other people=
.=E2=80=9D The shareholders assume that the externalities will be internali=
zed, that the harms that the company does to others will be revisited on th=
e company, which will lower the value of their shares. So the stock price f=
alls and the shareholders sue.This theory =E2=80=94=C2=A0whether it=E2=80=
=99s about ESG investing or everything-is-securities-fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0h=
as to=C2=A0assume=C2=A0some mechanism for the future internalizing of exter=
nalities.[4] A claim like =E2=80=9C80% of hydrocarbons will be stranded=E2=
=80=9D is essentially a claim about the future path of regulation, somethin=
g like =E2=80=9Cif the world wants to avoid warming by more than 2 degrees,=
 governments will need to impose strict limits on hydrocarbons, and the wor=
ld does want that so the governments will do that.=E2=80=9D A claim like =
=E2=80=9Cshareholders are harmed by Facebook putting profits over safety=E2=
=80=9D is a vaguer claim about regulation or consumer choices, something li=
ke =E2=80=9Cif Facebook keeps getting a reputation for not caring about saf=
ety people will stop using it or it will be banned or something, I dunno bu=
t seems bad.=E2=80=9DThose claims seem somewhat shaky to me.=C2=A0Do you th=
ink that world governments will come together to ban or limit oil drilling =
to limit=C2=A0climate change? Do you think governments will regulate Facebo=
ok in a way that harms Facebook, or that users will flee over the most rece=
nt controversies? I dunno, maybe, but my tendency is to bet on inaction in =
these areas.But does it matter? If all the shareholders of all the oil comp=
anies go to them and say =E2=80=9Cfind a way to stop drilling oil because e=
ventually there will be laws against it,=E2=80=9D and the oil companies do =
what the shareholders want and pivot away from oil, and new oil projects ca=
n=E2=80=99t get financed because investors all think that they are not viab=
le in the long run, then the problem is solved,=C2=A0even if governments ne=
ver actually pass laws against it. Shareholder assumptions about long-term =
viability can=C2=A0create=C2=A0(or destroy) long-term viability; the predic=
tions about future regulation don=E2=80=99t have to come true for this to w=
ork. Similarly, if Facebook=E2=80=99s shares drop due to whatever the lates=
t controversy is, guess what, shareholders have a securities-fraud claim, e=
ven if whatever they are worried about (regulation, loss of market share, e=
tc.) never happens and the shares eventually recover.And because the assump=
tions about future regulation or market reaction or whatever don=E2=80=99t =
need to be true for this whole struture to work, nobody needs to emphasize =
them all that much. ESG investors can push for sustainability as a way to a=
chieve long-term value without tying it directly to predictions about regul=
ation; oil companies have to plan for a lower-emissions world=C2=A0because =
their shareholders tell them to.And you can go to the SEC and say =E2=80=9C=
Facebook is harming shareholders by putting profits over safety.=E2=80=9D E=
veryone understands, now, that profit=C2=A0is not the only thing shareholde=
rs want.
