      Body language
   =20
 =20
One topic in finance that fascinates me is =E2=80=9Cbody language.=E2=80=9D=
 Here is the problem:=09Big   institutional investors   often meet one-on-o=
ne with the executives of the public companies whose shares they own.=09The=
se meetings appear to be   desirable and informative, to the point that inv=
estors will pay banks for   setting them up, and investors seem to make mar=
ket-beating trades after these meetings.=09However, it is illegal for compa=
nies to give the investors =E2=80=9Cmaterial nonpublic information=E2=80=9D=
 in these meetings.=09So what do they talk about?=09One theory is that the =
company tells investors information that is found in its public filings, an=
d they chat about the weather and stuff, but the investors observe the exec=
utives=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Cbody language=E2=80=9D during these meetings and u=
se it to inform their investing decisions.=09Like, the executives say =E2=
=80=9Cas we said in our earnings release, we had 14% gross margins this qua=
rter,=E2=80=9D and that is in fact in the earnings release so it=E2=80=99s =
not news. But if they say it confidently in a power pose the investors buy =
more, and if they say it nervously while looking to the side the investors =
sell everything. Body language.=09One assumes (why?) that this =E2=80=9Cbod=
y language=E2=80=9D is not=C2=A0itself=C2=A0material nonpublic information,=
 so there is no legal problem with the company giving the investors access =
to it.I don=E2=80=99t want to discount this theory entirely; I wrote once a=
bout a big investor that dumped all its stock of a public company because  =
its chairman was too tan, which makes sense and was in fact a good call. (T=
he company went bankrupt.) Still I do wonder about it sometimes. I assume =
=E2=80=9Cbody language=E2=80=9D is often a polite way to say =E2=80=9Cwell =
sure they say a=C2=A0few=C2=A0things that aren=E2=80=99t in the public fili=
ngs, but=C2=A0not important things.=E2=80=9D It is easier to draw a bright =
line of =E2=80=9Ctelling us earnings in advance is bad, but seeing body lan=
guage is fine=E2=80=9D than it is to say =E2=80=9Ctelling us earnings in ad=
vance is bad, but helping us with some technical questions about how we sho=
uld think about drivers of margin in our earnings model is fine.=E2=80=9D A=
nd no one=E2=80=99s in the meeting with you, so for all anyone knows it's j=
ust body language.Anyway here's a story about =E2=80=9CWhy Wall Street bank=
ers are hitting the road again=E2=80=9D that contains this amazing claim ab=
out body language:During in-person meetings, Knee, who previously worked at=
 Morgan Stanley and Goldman Sachs, pays attention to body language and look=
s out for subtle clues.When he asks tough questions about sensitive subject=
s, including compensation and sales targets, he is interested in the answer=
s, of course, but he also wants to see how an executive reacts to the inter=
rogation."You can do that on Zoom," Knee says. "But it's very hard to see t=
he sweat dripping down their forehead."I have to say I went to a lot of in-=
person meetings as an investment banker and at no point, ever, did I ask th=
e client a question and=C2=A0see the sweat dripping down their forehead?=C2=
=A0What? =E2=80=9CAnd I see revenue is up 4% quarter-on-quarter is that rig=
ht?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CUmm, umm, umm [looks around nervously] umm, umm, umm=
=C2=A0[breaks out in sweat] umm, umm, umm [tugs nervously at shirt collar] =
umm, umm, umm yes, yes our revenue is doing great, up 4% quarter-on-quarter=
, yes it sure is, nothing wrong with that, no siree, look over there a bird=
!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0I assume that the main advantage of in-person meetings over=
 emails and phone calls and Zoom is that if you sit in a room with a person=
 you are more likely to feel like you=E2=80=99re in it together, whatever i=
t is. There you are, in a room, being people together. There is no technolo=
gy intervening (or recording you for prosecutors to look at later). It is f=
un to gossip about people who aren=E2=80=99t there! When I was a banker I s=
ometimes went to meetings in person while colleagues from other groups dial=
ed in on a speakerphone, and there was always a sense that those of us in t=
he room =E2=80=94=C2=A0bankers and=C2=A0clients =E2=80=94=C2=A0were making =
fun of the people who dialed in, rolling our eyes at their communication la=
gs and slowness at picking up jokes, that we were the in crowd and they wer=
en=E2=80=99t part of the club. This was nonsense =E2=80=94=C2=A0often the p=
eople who dialed in were coverage bankers who knew the client well, while I=
 was some random guy=C2=A0from a product group who had just met them =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but the in-person dynamics were powerful. I can see why bankers wo=
uld want to get back to that.=C2=A0
