Behind the Crypto Broker Accused of  Enabling Ransomware Hackers. Grimes se=
en reading Karl Marx following split with world=E2=80=99s richest man Elon =
Musk.=C2=A0Bill Gross Found in Contempt of Court, Gets  Suspended Jail Time=
. China to ban video games featuring same-sex relationships, =E2=80=98effem=
inate=E2=80=99 men and moral choices.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0S=
tuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe a=
t this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg =
newsletters here. Thanks![1]=C2=A0I was, and remain,  cynical about the mea=
ning of this choice.[2] I summarized the framework as: =E2=80=9CThe idea he=
re is that a company makes money for shareholders ..., does some good for t=
he world ..., and also does some bad for the world .... The total value cre=
ated by the company (=E2=80=98stakeholder value=E2=80=99) is the sum of the=
 first two things =E2=80=94 shareholder value plus doing good for the world=
 =E2=80=94 minus the bad that the company does for the world. Over the long=
 run, the world will notice, rules and norms and consumer behavior will evo=
lve, and the company will have to internalize some of its (negative) extern=
alities: Companies that pollute will have to pay carbon taxes, companies th=
at are racist will lose employees and customers, etc. In the long run, shar=
eholder value approaches total societal value; a company that makes money f=
or shareholders at the cost of doing bad for the world will not be able to =
do that forever.=E2=80=9D=E2=88=82=C2=A0[3] Also in bad ways! Owning all th=
e companies does not necessarily align your interests with those of society=
; you want to maximize total shareholder value, not total social value. You=
 might prefer that all of your companies=C2=A0exploit workers and customers=
, for instance. The common-owners-as-coordinators model is often associated=
 with  the worry that this is an antitrust problem, because the diversified=
 common owners will push to keep prices high and not compete.[4] The common=
-ownership version of the argument supplies its own mechanism: The common o=
wners will force companies to internalize externalities because they also o=
wn the victims of those externalities.
