<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">The Facebook Files</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25230754.274064/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1=
lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8xMC8wMy90ZWNobm9sb2d5L3doaXN0bGUtYmxvd2VyLWZhY2Vib29rLWZyYW=
5jZXMtaGF1Z2VuLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBab288ac6" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">New York T=
imes</a>=C2=A0on=C2=A0Facebook Inc. whistle-blower Frances Haugen, who disc=
losed a bunch of internal documents about all the bad stuff that Facebook a=
llegedly does:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In an interview =
with =E2=80=9C60 Minutes=E2=80=9D that aired Sunday, Ms. Haugen, 37, said s=
he had grown alarmed by what she saw at Facebook. The company repeatedly pu=
t its own interests first rather than the public=E2=80=99s interest, she sa=
id. So she copied pages of Facebook=E2=80=99s internal research and decided=
 to do something about it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99ve seen a bunch of social networks and it was substantially worse at Fac=
ebook than what I had seen before,=E2=80=9D Ms. Haugen said. She added, =E2=
=80=9CFacebook, over and over again, has shown it chooses profit over safet=
y.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Okay fine. Faceboo=
k is a for-profit company with obligations to its shareholders, and at vari=
ous points it has a choice between doing pro-social things that are expensi=
ve or doing anti-social things that maximize its profits. Sometimes (she as=
serts, and I don=E2=80=99t particularly disagree)=C2=A0it chooses profit ov=
er public good. This is not a huge surprise, incentives being what they are=
, but it is good for policymakers and the public to know about the particul=
ar cases. It is good=C2=A0because, if we know about these choices, we can m=
ake informed decisions about regulation and enforcement. If Facebook someti=
mes chose to=C2=A0<em>break the law=C2=A0</em>to maximize profit, then regu=
lators should punish it. If everything that Facebook does to maximize profi=
ts is=C2=A0<em>legal</em>, but some of it is=C2=A0<em>horrible</em>, then w=
e should write=C2=A0<em>new laws=C2=A0</em>to make the horrible stuff illeg=
al. If Facebook does things that are bad for the world then policymakers sh=
ould try to make it stop.=C2=A0Basic stuff.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>But here is another fact from that same Times article:</p><blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ms. Haugen has also filed a whistle-blower complai=
nt with the Securities and Exchange Commission, accusing Facebook of mislea=
ding investors with public statements that did not match its internal actio=
ns. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ms. Haugen=E2=80=99s complaint to t=
he S.E.C. was based on her document trove and consisted of many cover lette=
rs, seven of which were obtained by The Times. Each letter detailed a diffe=
rent topic =E2=80=94 such as Facebook=E2=80=99s role in spreading misinform=
ation after the 2020 election and the impact its products have on teenagers=
=E2=80=99 mental health =E2=80=94 and accused the company of making =E2=80=
=9Cmaterial misrepresentations and omissions in statements to investors and=
 prospective investors.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">She was so concerned about Facebook putting profits over the public good=
 that she filed a complaint with the SEC about how Facebook misleads=C2=A0<=
em>investors</em>. Schematically, the general form of this complaint is:</p=
><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;=
">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Facebook maximizes profits for share=
holders instead of caring about the public good.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">In its public statements, however, it says =E2=80=9Cwe care =
about the public good, not just maximizing profits for shareholders.=E2=80=
=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Shareholders are deceived: The=
y think that Facebook is committed to the public good and are sad to find o=
ut that it is only maximizing profits for them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Therefore Facebook should give the shareholders some money, t=
o compensate them for this=C2=A0deception. (Or it should give money to the =
SEC, which might share some of it with the shareholders and some of it with=
 the whistle-blower, to vindicate=C2=A0the right=C2=A0of shareholders not t=
o be deceived.)</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is=C2=A0<em>weir=
d</em>, right? That the shareholders are harmed by the company maximizing p=
rofits more than they expected? I don=E2=80=99t mean that it=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0<em>wrong</em>, or=C2=A0logically inconsistent; it makes sense if you su=
pply a few assumptions. (Something like: =E2=80=9CFacebook went too far in =
maximizing short-term profits, in a way that is bad for its brand image and=
 public perception, which will cause it to lose customers and be more stric=
tly regulated, which will be bad for profits, and for shareholders, in the =
long run.=E2=80=9D)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I just want to suggest =
that it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>weird</em>. There is a <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25230754.274064/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3JwZ292Lmxhdy5=
oYXJ2YXJkLmVkdS8yMDEyLzA2LzI2L3RoZS1zaGFyZWhvbGRlci12YWx1ZS1teXRoLw/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBa06f4f7f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">classic view</a> that the interests of=
=C2=A0<em>shareholders=C2=A0</em>and the interests of=C2=A0<em>society</em>=
 sometimes diverge, that sometimes companies put the financial interests of=
 their shareholders (profit) above the good of society, and that an importa=
nt job of government is to find and regulate those cases of market failure.=
 It=E2=80=99s cheaper to dump your industrial waste in a river than to pay =
for safe disposal, so companies do that to maximize profits, so governments=
 write laws to prevent them from doing that, etc. The shareholders say =E2=
=80=9Cfocus on profit above all else=E2=80=9D and society says =E2=80=9Cwel=
l not above <em>all=C2=A0</em>else.=E2=80=9D And then companies have an opt=
imization problem: They have to maximize profit, constrained only by stayin=
g within the rules.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is such a standard=
 view that=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25=
230754.274064/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
TktMDgtMTkvbWF4aW1pemUtc2hhcmVob2xkZXItdmFsdWUtdG9wLWNlb3MtbWlnaHQtYmUtb3B0=
aW5nLW91dA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8a349700" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a couple of years ago=
</a> the chief executive officers of a bunch of big companies said, in effe=
ct, =E2=80=9Cwe are going to stop caring only about shareholders and start =
caring about society.=E2=80=9D This was viewed as a=C2=A0<em>big change</em=
>. You have shareholders, you have society, they are adverse to each other,=
 you have to pick. The CEOs were like =E2=80=9Cusually we have picked share=
holders but now sometimes we will pick society.=E2=80=9D[1]</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">But I think this model is wrong. I mean, perhaps it <em>wa=
s</em> once right, but now it isn=E2=80=99t. Now shareholders increasingly =
come to the companies they own and say =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t maximize prof=
its for us, do what is best for society.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The basic theory is about long-term sustainability and internalizati=
on of externalities. The theory is that if a company chooses profit over so=
me other legitimate stakeholder interest (being nice to customers, treating=
 workers fairly, not polluting, not undermining democracy, etc.), then its =
profits will not be sustainable. Eventually the customers will take their b=
usiness elsewhere, the workers won=E2=80=99t produce good work, or governme=
nts will pass laws about=C2=A0pollution and democracy-undermining that will=
 destroy the company=E2=80=99s business. In the long run, externalities are=
 internalized: If you make a profit by harming society, eventually society =
is going to send you a bill for that harm, with interest. Long-term shareho=
lders want you to profit=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>harming society, so tha=
t you can keep profiting in the future.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Thi=
s theory has gotten a ton of traction and attention in the last decade. In =
particular it is=C2=A0at the core of ESG investing, investing that takes in=
to account environmental, social and governance factors. We <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25230754.274064/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMTQvZG9uLXQtc3BlbmQteW91=
ci1saXRlY29pbnMtYXQtd2FsbWFydA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5ab911dc" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 talked last month</a> about a presentation from ESG-ish activist fund Engi=
ne No. 1 LLC, which focused explicitly on this internalization-of-externali=
ties argument.[2] And I say =E2=80=9Cthe last decade=E2=80=9D because of th=
is article by Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Kate Mackenzie from last Friday about =E2=
=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25230754.274=
064/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDEvaG9=
3LXRoZS1maW5hbmNlLXdvcmxkLXN0YXJ0ZWQtdHVybmluZy1hZ2FpbnN0LWZvc3NpbC1mdWVscw=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf977a1a6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">How the Finance World Started T=
urning Against Fossil Fuels</a>=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">A quiet celebration took place in London last month. It marked t=
he 10th anniversary of the =E2=80=9CCarbon Bubble=E2=80=9D report, publishe=
d by the think tank Carbon Tracker Initiative, that=E2=80=99s become one of=
 the most influential arguments against burning fossil fuels. =E2=80=A6</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Carbon Tracker concluded that only a fifth of =
the 2.3 trillion tons of hydrocarbons could be extracted and used. The rest=
 would have to be left in the ground. It was a completely counterintuitive =
proposal to the corporate world. All that coal, oil and gas contributed to =
the value of companies and assets that sat in portfolios from New York to H=
ong Kong. Even if the goal was only partly realized, those holdings would p=
lummet.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CInvestors are thus left ex=
posed to the risk of unburnable carbon,=E2=80=9D the report said. They woul=
d be =E2=80=9Cstranded assets=E2=80=9D ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
The Carbon Bubble report introduced a completely new way of looking at the =
problem. Its authors pointed out another truth: the fossil fuel business ha=
d to go away if the planet were to survive, and being the last one out the =
door would be a colossal financial mistake.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">That is an argument of the form =E2=80=9Csure you can make a =
lot of money for shareholders now by pumping out oil, but in the long run y=
ou won=E2=80=99t be allowed to, so as shareholders we want you to stop doin=
g so much of that.=E2=80=9D That argument was in some sense=C2=A0<em>invent=
ed=C2=A0</em>10 years ago, and now it is close to a consensus among big ins=
titutional investors. Engine No. 1 got=C2=A0<em>Exxon Mobil Corp.</em> shar=
eholders to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/252307=
54.274064/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtM=
DUtMjcvZXh4b24tbG9zdC1hLWNsaW1hdGUtcHJveHktZmlnaHQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bb4a58fc2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> throw out some of the company=E2=80=99s directors</a> f=
or, roughly speaking, not taking climate change seriously enough. Just as a=
 matter of shareholder value.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But while thi=
s theory is closely associated with ESG investing, they are=C2=A0not identi=
cal. We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25230=
754.274064/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEt=
MDktMjAvaW52ZXN0bWVudC1iYW5raW5nLWlzLWNoZWFwLWlmLXlvdS1yZS1yaWNo/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBfdd2e93f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> also talked about it</a> through the lens=
 of index investing and common ownership: If the big diversified shareholde=
rs own=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>the companies, they care relatively less abou=
t any one company=E2=80=99s profit maximization and more about increasing t=
he overall value available to all companies, which is not quite the same th=
ing as increasing the overall welfare of the world but which is=C2=A0<em>re=
lated=C2=A0</em>to that. Broadly diversified institutional investors, the a=
rgument goes, will care more about the externalities created by any one com=
pany because they own all the other companies. If a company pollutes, that =
will be bad for other companies, and so the shareholders will tell it to st=
op. If a company develops a Covid-19 vaccine, that will be good for other c=
ompanies, and so the shareholders will push it to do that. Common ownership=
 of all the companies is a new way to coordinate economic activity, and it =
makes sense that it would <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/25230754.274064/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjAtMDItMjEvdGhlLWNvbXBhbmllcy1hcmUtb24tdGhlLXNhbWUtdGVhbQ/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB2ae6514c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> solve certain coordination problems</a=
>=C2=A0and cause companies to take a broader view.[3] We <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25230754.274064/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMjcvaW1wb3N0b3JzLW9uLXRoZS1=
kdWUtZGlsaWdlbmNlLWNhbGw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3a012cd8" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked=
 last week</a> about a shareholder proposal at Fox Corp. demanding that it =
give its viewers =E2=80=9Can accurate understanding of current events throu=
gh the exercise of journalistic integrity,=E2=80=9D because that would be=
=C2=A0good for the world and, thus, for the other companies in its sharehol=
ders' portfolios.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or of course I talk all t=
he time here about how =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/25230754.274064/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
